metadata.name: Shrine #38
metadata.description:
'Shrine' is partly inspired by the decorative ceramic creations of the 'Troika Pottery' of Cornwall (UK), and also by the boldness and geometric nature of mid-century modern art. 

In creating this project, a series of colorfully illustrated png layers are stacked. Each layer is selected at random from several options. This means that each output is a unique artwork.

To download a 1500x2000px PNG:
Click/tap 'open', then click/tap the image to make a "Download image" button appear.

metadata.name: Convection Drawings #51
metadata.description:
This system is a composite of two generative layers: and invisible force field, and a swarm of particles that move around and leave an inky trail on the screen. There are only two forces at play: gravity towards the center, and repulsion between the particles, which becomes more or less strong depending on the underlying force field. In other words, it is like the particles “shrink” or “grow” depending on their position.
These simple conditions create emergent behavior with most particles moving in loops, analogous to convective cells in a fluid with heterogeneous densities. 
Press [m] to show the particles and see the system dynamics more clearly. You can also double click/tap anywhere on the screen to move the center of gravity and generate a different drawing from the same force field. 

This script will adapt nicely to any screen size and ratio.

Controls:
[SPACE] to play/pause
[Double click / tap] to relocate the center of gravity
[r] to recenter gravity and restart the drawing
[m] to toggle between path drawing and particle swarm views
[i] to reveal the hidden force field
[s] to download capture
[f] to toggle fullscreen
[2] to [9] to generate and save a hi-res image at 2x, 3x, … your viewport size (wait for the drawing to finish – might take longer at higher resolutions)

Made with p5.js.

metadata.name: Glossolalia #289
metadata.description:
This series is ultimately about catharsis. The compositions can be chaotic and maybe even a little messy, but they also can be vibrant and diverse… which is really what this is trying to celebrate: diversity and expression.

Simply, it’s about the emotions associated with whatever frees you.

Please see the linked fxtext article (on the main project page) for a more in-depth dissection of the concept. It’s less of a technical discussion, and more about the experience of the artist, and how it became linked with the feelings they associate with the art.

In live mode:

For higher resolutions, you can append “&density=2” to the url to double the size, “&density=3” to triple, and so on.
(This is highly recommended.)

To adjust grain, you can append “&grain=##” to the url. 40 is the default, and 0 will remove it completely.

metadata.name: Flowingcles #116
metadata.description:
"Flowingcles" is a generative art piece that showcases a mesmerizing collection of  circles and abstract shapes. This unique collection invites art enthusiasts to embark on an inspiring visual journey.

Some pieces feature abstract shapes accompanied by a noise effect, reflecting restlessness and energy, while others present a more serene atmosphere with minimalized noise effects. These two approaches offer collectors the freedom to choose the one that resonates with them the most.

The "Flowingcles" collection consists of a total of 128 original pieces. Each artwork has been generated with a unique combination, ensuring individuality and distinctiveness. By incorporating these pieces into their collections, art enthusiasts can adorn their homes, offices, or galleries with a sense of unparalleled art experience and authenticity.

"Flowingcles" stands as a prominent example of modern art, showcasing dynamism, aesthetics, and originality. This collection pushes the boundaries of art and takes viewers on a captivating visual journey. Therefore, me invite art lovers to explore the "Flowingcles" collection and become a part of this visual spectacle:)

- S: Save a png file with the current resolution (2400*3400)

metadata.name: Summer Vibes #19
metadata.description:
This collection was created using p5.js coding to create the artwork. The artwork is layered into its current form through p5.js coding in order to create the artwork shown available here.

The color palette was selected to reflect the vibrations of summer. Summer is a beautiful time of year, with activities in the daytime and the night. The figures that appear in the artwork were created by using the p5.js code to manipulate nested triangles. 

The goal of the line work was produced with p5.js and was created to reflect the warmth, dynamic activity, and quiet moments found during the long days and short nights of summer.

metadata.name: Schwere See #272
metadata.description:
Schwere See (...which is german for "Heavy Seas") this work creates completely generative ocean worlds between the real and the surreal. what is real? when do we feel reality? i guess as with many other things, we feel reality best when we're deprived of it. That might be the reason why it never ceases to fascinate us to both exaggerate and abstract nature and reality - maybe even at the same time. that's where this work tries to go... giving my best to create realistic looking waves out of hmm... thin electron-gas..., and then disrupt those from realism by unnaturally exaggerating waveforms and abstracting the display to a few colors and lines - ...well, not so few of the latter, actually ;-) beware: this needs a good GPU (at least here in 2023) to properly run in realtime. stills can still be rendered on a low end machine with on-board graphics, but for realtime playing you'd need some proper dedicated graphics card. and of course it wont run fast (or maybe not all) on your mobile phone (except maybe on a very high end device). the different mints vary in wave shape, color, camera view, animation speed, aspect ratio, frame style, hatching density, field of view, and more. some color schemes are based on pre-chosen palettes (slightly varied though), but others are wildly random-generated. there's always some risk in randomness, but lets give the error some chance to surprise us - this is one of the many benefits of generative art. as generative art can do so much more than just generate/show an image i feel almost obliged to add the possibility to animate/inteact. however, this extra control shall not be chosen without some considerations. you don't want a strobingly wild animation above your fireplace or in a doctors waiting room. nor is it motion-wise very inspiring to have subtle image stills hanging in a dancefloor. so, by default when in animation mode (-key) the scene is very slowly and steadily changing - some pieces faster, some slower. however, by pressing you can toggle to a sped up animation of waves, clouds, and scene rotation. btw, going faster in nav-mode also speeds up the wave animation. (...so be careful when you accelerate! the ocean is not a ponyfarm.) mouse/keyboard functions: ..........rotate view .........zoom in/out ...............start animation (or append '&AnimEnable=1' to the url) +<1><2><3><4>...make png screenshot in 1/2/3/4-fold resolution

...................same as +<3> ...................toggle nav-mode - navigate/fly through scene /.........accelerate in nav-mode /.......decelerate in nav-mode /.......rotate left in nav-mode /......rotate right in nav-mode ...................fast animation mode (speeds up animation) some technical info: technically this is a raymarched scene. the distance field of the waves is constructed my many localized rotations on many different scales. for the hatching no actual lines are being drawn. it is archieved by applying periodic functions in world-position-space as halftone patterns to the actual image color. the frequency of these halftone-functions thereby depending on screen-position-derivatives.

metadata.name: Souvenir (induit) d'une visite au musée #17
metadata.description:
Don't you remember?

We had a coffee and then went to the museum.
We saw this piece together.

Where was it?
It was in the second room on the left wall.

After the visit we went to the restaurant, or maybe not, I don't remember this part.

I just remember you. And the reflection of the light in your eyes.

metadata.name: CHX-1 #170
metadata.description:
Glitching pixels like it’s 1999.

Inspired by 90’s digital aesthetics, CHX-1 takes a random selection of GAN seeds, combines them in unique ways, and processes them –individually and as a group– with a series of glitching dithering algorithms. Generating fun, original, colorful artworks. Millions of possibilities. Have fun!

<<< Base seeds generated offline using personal styleGAN2-ADA models. Image processing and combinations done generatively by the CHX-1 algorithm >>>

GAN –> p5js –> Blockchain


• Artworks can take a few seconds to load when running live code.

• Press “s” (when "open live" is active) to save a PNG image.

metadata.name: A Bugged Forest #80
metadata.description:
A forest has stories to tell.
About times that were, about times that will be.
-
This project was minted in much unusual conditions. 
We gathered here, by 38 degrees heat. We belong to a crowd who loves stories, of civilisations at stake and deities, of afterlife and worship. We drank and hugged and chanted pagan hymns. We minted the Bugged Forest from our place on earth that we call Hell just for the fun of it. We are passionate, and loving, and angry and desperate. We, people of the soil, under a bugged sun.
-
This project is the long-form version of an algorithm that contains a bug. “The Bugged Tree”’s code was salvaged and stored and served as the core motivation and engine for an entire forest. Its concept is about releasing the control. I am a  byproduct of evolution, an iteration of that specie who wanted utter control, and which at some point, lost control over its own creation. As a generative artist, I chose to welcome the event of chance into my creative process. The symbolism in chance made me feel humble and free. Unwilling to make any change to a story that the Tree needed to tell me, as a listener, rather than a writer of my own idealised fantasies.
-
The iterations aren’t under control. They may be odd and off. We have to accept it. They are also plottable, press [s] in live mode to get a SVG. Attempt the plot at your own risk, as there’s a possibility for it to come near to impossibilities or cause paper or motor damage, and most certainly, a bugged drawing.
-
From Earth or from Hell, with love, yours truthfully, NFTBiker and zancan

metadata.name: Action; System #8
metadata.description:
Action; system is an experimental study inspired by the work of François Morellet. Morellet was one of the founders of the Groupe de Recherche d'Art Visuel (GRAV), founded in the 60s. His work was often informed by systems, a set of rules that determine the artwork, reducing the artist's subjectivity to a minimum.

This work explores what happens when we let go of the strict rule set. Do we ever fully let go?

-----------------
This work was released for the 2023 fundraising exhibition Cure3, and all of the proceeds and 1% of royalties will go to Parkinson's research funds. You can find more information at https://cure3.co.uk/.

-----------------
Controls
- R: new randomized output (the chances of recovering one of these outputs are very slim, that's what the next control is for)
- E: high-res output
- Double click: fullscreen

While you see the eye of Horus, your artwork is loading.

------------------
Made with p5.js & glsl
